{
  "texts": [
    "However, the semantically connected nature of sections in scientific papers presents challenges for directly summarizing them into coherent abstracts.",
    "Some extractive summarization studies adopt divide-and-conquer approaches, extracting key sentences from each section and then connecting them into a summary (Gidiotis & Tsoumakas, 2020; Miao et al., 2019).",
    "However, these studies only use rules-based methods to locate the firstlevel titles of the sections, ignoring the fact that scientific papers do not follow a uniform structure, in other words, the titles provided by authors exhibit flexibility and diversity, which is particularly evident across different fields.",
    "For example, in the computer science field, when authors propose a new model, they tend to name the chapter according to their specific model (Zhang et al., 2024a).",
    "In such cases, it is difficult to accurately locate titles and corresponding content using rule-based methods."
  ]
}